<h2>CSS3 Layout Modules</h2>
<a href="http://www.fivesimplesteps.com/products/css3-layout-modules" target="_blank">CSS3 Layout Modules</a> by Rachel Andrew was the first book out of the set I chose to read as I could remember a talk on the subject from Canvas Conference last year which I found very interesting.

<p>The book goes into detail about:</p>
<ul>
  <li><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Guide/CSS/Using_multi-column_layouts" target="_blank">Multi Column Layout</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Guide/CSS/Flexible_boxes" target="_blank">Flexbox</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://css-tricks.com/almanac/properties/g/grid/" target="_blank">CSS grid layout</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://dev.opera.com/articles/view/an-introduction-to-css-regions/" target="_blank">CSS Regions</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://css3clickchart.com/#exclusions" target="_blank">CSS exclusions</a></li>
</ul>

<p>I'm obviously not going to go into what they all are so have included links up there to the best demos I can find.</p>
<p>This book was a great way to hear about the newest parts of the CSS spec and after reading this I was left very intrigued, but a little disappointed that I can't use them fully yet! When they are properly implemented I know they'll be so useful in giving us developers more control and variety over the style of content using pure CSS, without losing any semantic value in the markup.</p>

